This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a method for human action recognition in video using convolutional neural networks. The use of support vector machines for classification also suggests that it may belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves preprocessing techniques, which could place it in the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The use of video data suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of neural networks and SVMs suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
